<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><xmi:XMI xmlns:type3="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/frequency/tfidf/type.ecore" xmlns:cas="http:///uima/cas.ecore" xmlns:type4="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/metadata/type.ecore" xmlns:dependency="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/syntax/type/dependency.ecore" xmlns:type8="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/syntax/type.ecore" xmlns:type9="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/type.ecore" xmlns:type5="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/ner/type.ecore" xmlns:type6="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/segmentation/type.ecore" xmlns:tcas="http:///uima/tcas.ecore" xmlns:pathos="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/argumentation/types/pathos.ecore" xmlns:tweet="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/lexmorph/type/pos/tweet.ecore" xmlns:chunk="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/syntax/type/chunk.ecore" xmlns:type7="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/semantics/type.ecore" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:type2="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/coref/type.ecore" xmlns:toulmin="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/argumentation/types/toulmin.ecore" xmlns:morph="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/lexmorph/type/morph.ecore" xmlns:types="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/argumentation/types.ecore" xmlns:constituent="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/syntax/type/constituent.ecore" xmlns:type="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/anomaly/type.ecore" xmlns:pos="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/lexmorph/type/pos.ecore" xmi:version="2.0"><cas:NULL xmi:id="0"/><cas:Sofa xmi:id="1" sofaNum="1" sofaID="_InitialView" mimeType="text" sofaString="Home educators , perhaps unsurprisingly, seem to be quite a vociferous lobby. It certainly takes time and effort to to educate one's children at home so credit to their courage in this respect. &#10;This is an article on cif so i take it that it's intention is to open a debate. In using the terms &quot;selfish&quot; and &quot;cocooning&quot; I'm not trying to tarnish this group out of some misplaced prejudice. &#10;It is my contention that school offers opportunities and experiences to children that cannot be replicated elsewhere. This isn't purely about learning. Children, fortunately, are natural when it comes to learning and that inbuilt curiosity will stand them in good stead. &#10;I believe there is something that is bigger than the family. This is our social environment. Our society is a patchwork of great subtlety. Children benefit from meeting other children from different cultures and backgrounds. &#10;This might sound a bit cranky but there is a social benefit in letting children run around the recreation ground with lots of other kids of their own age, raising their energy levels and enabling them to experience camaraderie with their peers. &#10;My point about social capital - in the sense of the term used by Bourdieu - is that elites reproduce and that in taking kids out of school whether to educate them in the private sector or at home is not a progressive step. &#10;The authors only cite their own research I see and are keen on &quot;educational freedom&quot; and against &quot;officialdom&quot;. &#10;You know it was &quot;officialdom&quot; who took children out of factories in the XIX century. Officials also let down Khyra Ishaq who never had the chance to go to school. &#10;Finally, if some home educators cannot construct arguments and debate in a civilised manner one wonders what how well they transmit intellectual skills. &#10;Or is their goal to get to GCSEs and then out-source back to the public sector? A kind of self-service canteen model? "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1908" language="en" documentId="1138" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="pastis" date="29 July 2010 10:46am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6877032" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="2" thumbsDown="0" origId="1138" notes="" title="Home education: precious, not dangerous"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="194"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="195" end="390"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="391" end="662"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="663" end="888"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="889" end="1134"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="1135" end="1358"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="63" sofa="1" begin="1359" end="1471"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="67" sofa="1" begin="1472" end="1635"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="71" sofa="1" begin="1636" end="1789"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="75" sofa="1" begin="1790" end="1908"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55 59 63 67 71 75"/></xmi:XMI>